INSERT INTO `products` VALUES (1,'places','Beirut','? Raouche Rock','The Timeless Legend of Raouche Rock','Iconic coastal landmark, perfect for sunset views and seaside walks.','Rising majestically from the Mediterranean Sea, Raouché Rock—also known as the Pigeons\' Rock—stands as one of Beirut’s most iconic and enduring natural landmarks. These impressive limestone formations have weathered centuries of waves, wind, and shifting coastlines, creating a breathtaking silhouette at the edge of the Raouché district. Beyond their geological intrigue, the rocks hold a powerful place in Lebanese cultural memory. Local legend speaks of a monstrous sea creature defeated by a heroic figure, its fall splitting the rock into the twin arches seen today—a symbol of resilience and victory. Other stories connect the site to ancient Phoenician rituals, maritime tales, and the deep spiritual bond between the Lebanese people and the sea. Throughout modern history, Raouché has remained a gathering place for poets, fishermen, families, and travelers, each drawn to its dramatic cliffs and tranquil horizon. At sunset, when the sky glows gold and orange behind the rocks, the scene becomes almost timeless, capturing the essence of Lebanon’s coastal beauty and the enduring spirit of Beirut itself','/images/raouche.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2,'places','Beirut','? Zeytuna Bay','Zaitunay Bay: Beirut\'s Modern Seaside Escape','Zeytuna Bay, a serene coastal, is a must-visit destination for anyone seeking a tranquil escape.','Nestled along the glistening coastline of Beirut\'s central district, Zaitunay Bay is a modern waterfront promenade that seamlessly blends luxury, leisure, and breathtaking sea views. Conceived as part of the city’s ambitious post-war regeneration, the bay transformed what was once a quiet stretch of docklands into a vibrant, cosmopolitan destination that stretches elegantly along the Marina beside the historic Saint George Bay. Today, the promenade is lined with stylish restaurants, chic cafés, and boutiques that reflect Beirut’s unique mix of Mediterranean charm and urban sophistication. Visitors can enjoy peaceful strolls along the wooden boardwalk, where yachts gently sway in the harbor and the salty breeze carries the scent of the sea. As daylight fades and the sky turns shades of amber and violet, the bay comes alive with families, couples, and friends gathering to dine al fresco, sip Lebanese wine, or simply take in the serene coastal atmosphere. With its harmonious blend of modern architecture, relaxed elegance, and maritime spirit, Zaitunay Bay has become not only a favorite social hub but also a symbol of Beirut’s resilience, creativity, and enduring connection to the Mediterranean.','/images/zeytuna.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(3,'places','Beirut','? Beirut Souks','Beirut Souks: Where History Meets Modern Elegance','Beirut Souks is a signature shopping, hospitality, entertainment and cultural meeting place.','Located in the heart of Lebanon\'s vibrant capital, the Beirut Souks represent a harmonious blend of ancient heritage and contemporary urban elegance. Long before the rise of modern Beirut, this area served as the bustling commercial center of the ancient and medieval city—a maze of lively alleyways where merchants traded spices, textiles, precious metals, handcrafted goods, and local delicacies. The scents, colors, and sounds of the souks once defined daily life, making them a crossroads of culture and commerce in the Eastern Mediterranean. Although much of the district was devastated during the Lebanese Civil War, its spirit was rekindled through an extensive reconstruction project led by Solidere, which sought to revive the souks while preserving the deep historical layers beneath them. Today, the Beirut Souks stretch across open-air promenades filled with international luxury brands, innovative Lebanese designers, stylish cafés, cinemas, and spacious plazas that host concerts, art exhibitions, seasonal festivals, and community events. Yet beneath the polished walkways lie archaeological remains, ancient street grids, and traces of long-lost marketplaces—quietly telling the story of millennia of trade and cultural exchange. More than just a shopping destination, the Beirut Souks embody the resilience and identity of Beirut itself, where tradition and modernity coexist in a lively, ever-evolving urban heartbeat.','/images/beirutsouks.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(4,'places','Beirut','? Beirut Downtown','Beirut Downtown: The Heartbeat of a Resilient City','Beirut Downtown, a captivating blend of ancient history, is a must-visit destination for any traveler to Lebanon.','Beirut Downtown, also known as Centre Ville, is the vibrant heart of Lebanon’s capital—a place where layers of history, culture, and modern life seamlessly intertwine. Once the bustling center of ancient Berytus, it housed Roman colonnaded streets, Ottoman-era souks, elegant French Mandate buildings, and lively public markets that made it a true crossroads of civilizations. The Lebanese Civil War, however, left much of this treasured district shattered, its streets emptied and its landmarks reduced to ruins. Yet in the 1990s, a massive reconstruction effort led by Solidere sparked an extraordinary transformation, meticulously restoring historical facades while introducing modern infrastructure, refined urban planning, and contemporary architecture. Today, Downtown Beirut stands as a testament to the city’s resilience and capacity for renewal. Its elegant boulevards are lined with luxury boutiques, stylish cafés, art galleries, cultural institutions, and renovated heritage buildings that reflect the city’s cosmopolitan character. Iconic spaces such as Martyrs\' Square, Place de l’Étoile, and the Beirut Souks draw locals and visitors alike, offering a blend of leisure, history, and vibrant city life. As people wander through its streets, they encounter Roman archaeological sites, grand mosques like Mohammad Al-Amin, historic churches, modern skyscrapers, and tree-lined promenades—all coexisting in a striking urban tapestry. More than just a commercial district, Beirut Downtown embodies the enduring spirit of Lebanon, serving as a living dialogue between its storied past, its dynamic present, and its ever-evolving future.','/images/downtown.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(5,'places','Beirut','? National Museum of Beirut','National Museum of Beirut: Guardian of Lebanon\'s Heritage','The National Museum is home to an extraordinary collection of important archaeological objects.','The National Museum of Beirut stands as Lebanon’s foremost archaeological institution and a profound symbol of cultural endurance. Situated along the former Green Line—the dividing path that once separated East and West Beirut during the civil war—the museum not only witnessed years of intense conflict but miraculously survived them. Its dedicated staff undertook extraordinary measures to safeguard its priceless artifacts, encasing statues in concrete, burying mosaics under protective layers, and sealing delicate pieces in sandbags to shield them from shelling and looting. Thanks to their heroic efforts, much of the collection emerged intact, allowing future generations to experience the depth of Lebanon’s past. Today, the fully restored museum is a jewel of national heritage, with beautifully curated galleries that guide visitors through thousands of years of history—from prehistoric settlements and Phoenician maritime culture to the grandeur of the Roman and Byzantine eras and the artistic richness of the Islamic period. Among its most iconic pieces are the Phoenician anthropoid sarcophagi, mesmerizing Roman frescoes, intricate gold jewelry, and monumental limestone statues. Thoughtfully designed multimedia displays and warm, atmospheric lighting bring these ancient civilizations to life, creating a powerful connection between past and present. More than a collection of artifacts, the National Museum of Beirut embodies the resilience, identity, and cultural pride of Lebanon, making it an essential destination for anyone seeking to understand the remarkable story of this land and its people.','/images/museum.webp',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(6,'places','North','? Cedars of God','The Sacred Legacy of the Cedars of God','One of Lebanon\'s oldest cedar forests, a UNESCO heritage site.','Nestled high in the rugged mountains of northern Lebanon, the Cedars of God are among the last precious remnants of the vast cedar forests that once blanketed the ancient Near East. These majestic trees—Cedrus libani, the pride of Lebanon—have been revered for thousands of years, celebrated in mythology, sacred texts, and the artistry of ancient civilizations. Their exceptional durability, aromatic wood, and resistance to decay made them one of the most sought-after materials of the ancient world. The Phoenicians built their legendary ships from cedar beams; the Egyptians used the wood for sarcophagi and ceremonial boats; and the Assyrians, Babylonians, and Persians coveted it for palaces, fortresses, and monumental temples. The Bible itself recounts that cedar wood was used to construct the famed Temple of Solomon in Jerusalem, further elevating the tree’s spiritual and cultural significance. Yet the cedar’s importance extends far beyond commerce and empire. For millennia, it has symbolized strength, eternity, and divine protection—a living emblem woven into Lebanon’s identity and even honored on its national flag. Today, protected as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, the Cedars of God form a serene sanctuary where ancient giants tower over winding mountain paths, their silhouettes etched against the crisp alpine sky. Walking among these millennia-old trees, visitors feel a profound sense of continuity, as if stepping into a timeless landscape that has silently witnessed the rise and fall of civilizations. More than a forest, the Cedars of God stand as a living monument to Lebanon’s natural heritage, resilience, and enduring spiritual legacy.','/images/cedars.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(7,'places','North','? Batroun','Batroun: Coastal Charm and Ancient Roots','Charming coastal town with Phoenician walls and vibrant nightlife.','Batroun, a picturesque coastal town in northern Lebanon, is a mesmerizing fusion of ancient heritage and modern Mediterranean charm. Believed to have been founded by the Phoenicians as early as the 14th century BCE, it ranks among the world’s oldest continuously inhabited cities and has long served as a strategic maritime gateway on the Eastern Mediterranean. One of its most remarkable features is the famed Phoenician sea wall—an extraordinary feat of ancient engineering crafted to shield the harbor from powerful waves. Remarkably, sections of this wall still stand today, silently testifying to the ingenuity of the civilization that built it. Over the centuries, Batroun evolved under the influence of Romans, Byzantines, Crusaders, and Ottomans, each leaving behind layers of architecture, fortifications, churches, and charming alleyways that give the town its unique atmosphere. Yet Batroun is far from being just a historical treasure. It has blossomed into a vibrant cultural hub known for its artisanal lemonade, lively nightlife, boutique guesthouses, and beautiful stone homes draped in bougainvillea. Visitors can stroll through narrow cobblestone streets, explore landmarks like St. Stephan’s Cathedral and the old Maronite and Greek Orthodox quarters, or simply relax by the turquoise sea where swimmers and fishermen share the calm waters. With its warm coastal ambiance, deep-rooted history, and welcoming spirit, Batroun offers a captivating harmony between Lebanon’s ancient past and its sunlit, contemporary Mediterranean lifestyle.','/images/batroun.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(8,'places','North','? Byblos','Byblos: Cradle of Civilization','Byblos is a very charming city distinguished for its ancient souks.','Byblos, one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities on Earth, is a living chronicle of human civilization nestled along Lebanon’s shimmering Mediterranean coast. Known as Gubla to the ancient Phoenicians and Gebal in the Bible, this legendary city played a pivotal role in shaping the cultural and intellectual foundations of the ancient Near East. It was from Byblos that the Phoenician alphabet—one of humanity’s greatest innovations and the ancestor of most modern writing systems—began its spread across the world, influencing Greek, Latin, and countless scripts that followed. As a bustling maritime hub, Byblos forged vital connections between Egypt, Mesopotamia, Cyprus, and the Aegean, thriving on trade in prized commodities such as papyrus, Lebanese cedar wood, and the rare purple dye coveted by ancient royalty.Across millennia, the city witnessed the rise and fall of powerful empires—Egyptian, Assyrian, Babylonian, Persian, Hellenistic, Roman, Byzantine, Crusader, and Ottoman—each leaving behind architectural marvels and cultural traces that form the city’s unique archaeological tapestry. Today, visitors can explore these layered remnants of history firsthand: from Neolithic dwellings and Phoenician temples to Roman colonnades, Byzantine basilicas, medieval ramparts, and the imposing Crusader castle that overlooks the sea. Yet Byblos is far more than an open-air museum. Its old souks buzz with artisans and cafés, fishing boats sway peacefully in the picturesque harbor, and the scent of the sea mingles with that of local cuisine.','/images/byblos.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(9,'places','North','? Harissa Jounieh','Harissa: The Sacred Heights of Lebanon','Harissa, a picturesque town, is a significant religious and cultural destination in Lebanon.','Perched high above the sweeping Bay of Jounieh, Harissa stands as one of Lebanon’s most cherished spiritual sanctuaries and a breathtaking destination for both pilgrims and travelers seeking serenity. Crowned by the majestic statue of Our Lady of Lebanon, this hilltop site has become a symbol of faith, hope, and national unity for all Lebanese. Erected in 1908, the gleaming white statue of the Virgin Mary—with her arms outstretched in blessing—rests upon a spiraling stone pedestal that visitors can climb to admire spectacular, unobstructed views of the Mediterranean Sea, the bustling coastline, and the mountains rolling inland. At the base of the statue lies an intimate chapel that radiates quiet devotion, while just steps away rises the impressive Maronite Cathedral of Saint Paul, easily recognizable by its contemporary domes, sweeping arches, and shimmering mosaics that blend tradition with modern artistry.Reaching Harissa is an experience in itself. While many ascend by road, countless visitors choose the iconic Téléphérique, a cable car journey that drifts gracefully over pine forests, terracotta rooftops, and the vibrant cityscape below—turning the pilgrimage into a moment of pure wonder. The air grows cooler and calmer as one approaches the sanctuary, creating a natural sense of peace and reflection. Whether one comes to pray, admire the architecture, or simply absorb the majestic scenery, Harissa embodies the profound spiritual heritage of Lebanon and offers a rare vantage point where nature, culture, and faith meet in perfect harmony.','/images/harrissa.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(10,'places','North','? Jeita Grotto','Jeita Grotto: Lebanon\'s Underground Wonder','Discover the breathtaking beauty of Jeita Grotto, a UNESCO World Heritage site featuring stunning caves.','Hidden beneath the emerald hills of the Nahr el-Kalb Valley, Jeita Grotto stands as one of Lebanon’s most extraordinary natural wonders—a mesmerizing network of limestone caverns stretching for more than 9 kilometers underground. Though known to ancient inhabitants, the grotto was rediscovered in the 19th century, unveiling a subterranean world sculpted by water over millions of years. Today, it is divided into two breathtaking sections, each offering a unique experience. The Upper Grotto, reached by cable car and explored on foot, unveils immense chambers adorned with towering stalactites and stalagmites, delicate stone draperies, and formations so intricate they seem almost handmade. One of its crowning marvels is the world’s longest known stalactite, hanging like a colossal crystal spear from the cavern ceiling. Below, the Lower Grotto invites visitors into a dreamlike journey by boat, gliding silently along an underground river that reflects shimmering mineral surfaces and illuminates hidden passages carved by time.The grotto’s cathedral-like halls, echoing stillness, and surreal rock sculptures create an atmosphere that feels both ancient and sacred—as if stepping into nature’s own underground palace. Beyond its geological grandeur, Jeita Grotto has grown into a powerful national symbol, representing Lebanon in international campaigns and embodying the country’s natural beauty, resilience, and creative spirit. Nominated as one of the New 7 Wonders of Nature, it continues to captivate travelers from around the world. For those seeking tranquility, Jeita Grotto remains an unforgettable journey into the depths of Lebanon’s natural heritage.','/images/jeitta.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,'places','North','? Beiteddine Palace','Beiteddine Palace: Jewel of the Chouf Mountains','Situated high amongst the Chouf Mountains is a stunning terraced gardens and orchards.','Perched gracefully amid the rolling hills and terraced villages of Lebanon’s Chouf region, the Beiteddine Palace is a magnificent testament to the country’s artistic brilliance and cultural depth—a jewel of 19th-century architecture that continues to captivate all who walk through its grand gates. Commissioned by Emir Bashir Shihab II in the late 18th century and completed over several decades in the early 180s, the palace served as both the emir’s residence and the political heart of Mount Lebanon. Its name, meaning “House of Faith,” echoes the pride and significance the complex held for the Shihab dynasty and the surrounding communities. Blending exquisite Lebanese stonework with Ottoman elegance and subtle Italian influences, the palace unfolds in a series of breathtaking courtyards adorned with marble fountains, geometric mosaics, arched colonnades, and richly carved cedar-wood ceilings that showcase the craftsmanship of the era.Inside, visitors discover a world of artistic beauty: rooms decorated with delicate frescoes, inlaid furniture, stained-glass windows, and intricate stone carvings that reflect both local traditions and the cosmopolitan tastes of the emir’s court. One of the palace’s most remarkable features is its outdoor museum of Byzantine mosaics, where centuries-old masterpieces discovered in the region are displayed under open skies, creating a striking dialogue between history and landscape. Surrounded by fragrant gardens and dramatic mountain scenery, Beiteddine today stands not only as a preserved historical monument but also as a flourishing cultural hub. Each summer, the palace comes alive with the renowned Beiteddine Festival, welcoming artists, musicians, and audiences from around the world.','/images/beiteddine.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(12,'places','South','? Tyre Ruins','The Ruins of Tyre: Echoes of a Maritime Empire','Ancient Roman ruins with hippodrome and necropolis by the sea.','The ruins of Tyre, scattered across the city’s southern and eastern districts, stand as powerful echoes of the splendor, influence, and resilience of one of the ancient Mediterranean’s greatest seaports. Founded by the Phoenicians and renowned for its mastery of maritime trade, Tyre quickly became a cultural and economic powerhouse—coveted by empires from the Assyrians and Babylonians to the Persians, Greeks, and Romans, all of whom reshaped the city according to their ambitions. Today, its archaeological landscapes reveal layer upon layer of this extraordinary past. The Al-Bass Archaeological Site, located inland, is perhaps the most impressive: a sprawling complex that includes a vast Roman necropolis filled with intricately carved sarcophagi, a monumental triumphal arch marking the entrance to the ancient city, and one of the world’s largest and best-preserved hippodromes, where chariots once thundered along its elongated racetrack. Closer to the coast lies the Al-Mina site, a waterfront district where visitors can wander through remnants of colonnaded streets, grand bathhouses, residential quarters, and mosaic pavements that reflect the refined urban life of Roman Tyre.Together, these ruins paint a vivid portrait of a city that not only commanded the seas but helped shape the cultural and commercial networks of the ancient world. Now protected as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, the archaeological sites of Tyre preserve the architectural genius of successive civilizations while offering an immersive journey into a past where sailors, merchants, craftsmen, and conquerors once crossed paths. As waves crash gently against the shore and the sun sets over the Mediterranean, the ruins remind visitors that Tyre was—and remains—one of the great cradles of ancient civilization, a place where history rises proudly from the earth.','/images/TyreRuins.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(13,'places','South','? Sidon Sea Castle','Sidon Sea Castle: A Fortress on the Wave','Crusader fortress built on a small island connected by a bridge.','Sidon Sea Castle, perched at the entrance of Sidon’s historic harbor, is one of Lebanon’s most captivating medieval monuments and a striking testament to the city’s maritime legacy. Built by the Crusaders in the early 13th century on a small rocky island, the fortress was constructed over the remains of a much older Phoenician temple, symbolizing Sidon’s continuous layers of history. Its strategic position allowed it to protect the bustling port, control trade routes, and withstand repeated assaults from rival powers. A narrow stone causeway, rebuilt during the Mamluk period, links the castle to the mainland and leads visitors toward its imposing walls, rugged towers, and arched gateways shaped by centuries of wind and waves. Inside, the castle reveals a labyrinth of vaulted chambers, stairways, and lookout points that once served as military quarters and defensive platforms. The upper terrace offers sweeping views of Sidon’s old souks, the modern cityscape, and the shimmering Mediterranean stretching endlessly beyond. Over time, the structure has been modified by both Mamluks and Ottomans, blending Crusader solidity with Islamic architectural refinements. Today, Sidon Sea Castle stands not only as an archaeological gem but as a vivid window into the city’s dynamic past—a place where ancient Phoenicians, medieval knights, merchants, and sailors all left their mark. With its atmospheric ruins, tranquil harbor setting, and rich historical layers, the castle remains one of Lebanon’s most iconic coastal landmarks and an essential stop for anyone exploring the heritage of Sidon.','/images/SidonSeaCastle.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(14,'places','Bekaa','? Baalbek Temples','The Majestic Ruins of Baalbek','Massive Roman temples with grand columns in the heart of the Bekaa.','Nestled in the fertile heart of the Bekaa Valley, Baalbek stands as one of the most awe-inspiring archaeological treasures in the Middle East—a monumental reminder of the civilizations that once flourished on Lebanese soil. Known as Heliopolis, or the “City of the Sun,” during Roman times, Baalbek was a grand religious center attracting pilgrims from across the empire to worship Jupiter, Venus, and Bacchus. The scale of the complex is staggering: the six remaining columns of the Temple of Jupiter rise nearly 23 meters high, among the tallest ever constructed by the Romans, and are supported by enormous stone blocks whose transportation and placement still puzzle engineers today. Nearby, the remarkably preserved Temple of Bacchus captivates visitors with its richly detailed friezes, mythological reliefs, and colossal doorway, offering a rare glimpse into the artistic mastery and religious devotion of the ancient world.Wandering through Baalbek’s vast courtyards, monumental staircases, and sunlit colonnades feels like stepping into a living chronicle of history—each stone echoing the footsteps of priests, emperors, traders, and poets who traveled here centuries ago. Layers of Phoenician, Roman, Byzantine, and Islamic influence intertwine in its architecture, reflecting the site’s long and complex past. Beyond its archaeological splendor, Baalbek has long held a spiritual and cultural significance that transcends time, inspiring travelers, historians, and artists with its grandeur and mystery. Today, it is not only a marvel of ancient engineering but also a symbol of Lebanon’s profound heritage, inviting visitors to experience an unforgettable journey through the mythology, majesty, and enduring spirit of a civilization that once worshipped the sun.','/images/baalbek.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(15,'places','Bekaa','? Anjar','Anjar: The Umayyad City of the Bekaa','Umayyad-era archaeological city featuring symmetrical design.','Located at the crossroads of ancient trade routes in the fertile Bekaa Valley, Anjar is a rare archaeological treasure that encapsulates a brief yet extraordinary chapter in early Islamic history. Founded in the early 8th century by the Umayyad Caliph al-Walid I, the city was conceived as a grand palace-complex that would embody the power, refinement, and urban vision of the Umayyad dynasty at its height. Unlike most ancient Lebanese cities that evolved organically over millennia, Anjar was meticulously planned from the ground up. Its grid-like layout—clearly influenced by Roman and Byzantine urban models—is organized around two main colonnaded avenues, the Cardo and the Decumanus, which intersect at a majestic tetrapylon. Within this structured framework lie the remains of palatial residences, ornate baths, defensive walls, mosques, audience halls, and commercial districts, all blending Greco-Roman architectural features with early Islamic design elements.What makes Anjar particularly compelling is its fleeting lifespan: occupied for less than a century, the city was abandoned following the fall of the Umayyads, leaving it frozen in time and remarkably well-preserved. This unusual historical pause allows visitors to witness an early Islamic city in its purest form, unmarred by later expansions or reconstructions. As a designated UNESCO World Heritage Site, Anjar stands as a powerful symbol of Lebanon’s multicultural tapestry, revealing the dynamic exchanges between Arab, Byzantine, and Persian worlds. Today, as travelers walk through its sunlit ruins, they experience a vivid glimpse into the sophistication, artistry, and political ambition that shaped the Umayyad civilization and left an indelible mark on the region’s history.','/images/anjar.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(16,'places','Bekaa','? Ammiq','Ammiq Wetland : Lebanon\'s Treasure','Ammiq Wetland is a pristine natural reserve nestled in the heart of Lebanon.','Tucked within the fertile expanse of the Bekaa Valley, the Ammiq Wetland is the largest surviving freshwater wetland in Lebanon and one of the most precious ecological sanctuaries in the Middle East. Once part of a vast marsh system that stretched across the valley, Ammiq has endured centuries of agricultural pressure, drainage attempts, and urban expansion, surviving largely thanks to determined conservation efforts and the remarkable resilience of its natural ecosystems. For thousands of years, the wetland has served as a critical stopover for migratory birds traveling between Europe, Asia, and Africa, earning it international recognition as a haven for ornithologists, researchers, and nature enthusiasts. During peak migration seasons, the skies fill with pelicans, storks, herons, eagles, and hundreds of other species, creating one of the most spectacular wildlife displays in the country.But Ammiq’s richness extends far beyond birdlife. Its mosaic of reed beds, freshwater pools, meadows, and winding streams shelters rare amphibians, colorful dragonflies, and elusive mammals such as the European otter, the wild boar, and even the endangered jungle cat. The surrounding landscape reflects centuries of rural tradition, where ancient agricultural techniques, grazing practices, and modern sustainability efforts coexist in harmony. Rustic footpaths invite visitors to explore the area on foot or by bicycle, offering peaceful encounters with Lebanon’s natural heritage far from the noise of the city. Today, the Ammiq Wetland stands not only as a biodiversity hotspot but also as a powerful symbol of environmental preservation in Lebanon—a serene refuge where travelers can reconnect with nature, witness the rhythms of wildlife, and appreciate the fragile beauty of one of the region’s last great wetlands.','/images/ammiq.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(17,'places','Bekaa','? Berdawni Zahle','Berdawni River in Zahle: The Beating Heart of the City of Wine','Berdawni isn\'t only about Casino Arabi, it\'s also about the tastiest ice cream in Zahle.','Flowing gently through the heart of Zahlé, the capital of the Bekaa Valley, the Berdawni River is far more than a simple waterway — it is the lifeblood of the city and one of its most cherished cultural symbols. Framed by lush trees, charming stone bridges, and the famous Berdawni Boulevard, the river has shaped the rhythm of daily life in Zahlé for centuries. Along its idyllic banks stretch the city’s renowned open-air restaurants, cafés, and pastry shops, where the sound of flowing water mingles with laughter, conversation, and the clinking of glasses filled with local arak. In the early 20th century, this enchanting riverside became a gathering place for Lebanon’s poets, politicians, and artists, earning Zahlé poetic titles such as the “Bride of the Bekaa” and the “City of Wine and Poetry.”Fed by cool mountain springs, the Berdawni’s crystal-clear waters weave through the valley, bringing freshness and vitality, especially during the scorching summer months when families and travelers seek refuge beneath the shade of its sycamores and willows. The riverfront’s vibrant atmosphere comes alive with the aroma of mezze, the melody of traditional music, and the warmth of Zahle’s legendary hospitality. Strolling along the promenade, crossing its bridges, or dining just steps from the water offers an experience that feels both timeless and unmistakably Lebanese. Today, the Berdawni remains one of Lebanon’s most beloved leisure destinations — a place where nature, culture, and conviviality come together to celebrate the enduring spirit of Zahlé.','/images/zahle.jpeg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(201,'hotels','Luxury','? Kempinski Summerland','Kempinski Summerland Hotel & Resort Beirut','Set against the Mediterranean Sea amidst the labyrinth of pools in Summerland Bay\'s private beach and marina, the stage is set for a truly memorable stay.','Luxury resort with beach and marina views.','/images/kempi.jpeg',NULL,33.87990000,35.48120000,'+9611888888'),(202,'hotels','Luxury','? Phoenicia Beirut','Phoenicia Beirut','Located in the heart of Beirut, the iconic InterContinental Phoenicia Beirut offers stunning views of the Mediterranean.','Iconic 5-star hotel in Beirut.','/images/phoe.avif',NULL,33.89540000,35.48460000,'+9611399999'),(203,'hotels','Luxury','? Le Royal Hotel','Le Royal Hotel','Sitting atop a hill and only 20 minutes from the airport, Le Royal Hotel offers breathtaking panoramic views.','Panoramic views 20 minutes from airport.','/images/leroyal.jpeg',NULL,33.92800000,35.58450000,'+9611234567'),(204,'hotels','Luxury','? Chtaura Park Hotel','Chtaura Park Hotel','Located in the heart of the Bekaa valley, the only 5 stars hotel with the ultimate luxury for ideal weekend getaways.','Luxury hotel in Bekaa valley.','/images/park.webp',NUL